{
  "text": "Notably, the layer-specific subtype production order can be partially recapitulated in both mouse-and human-derived cortical cells in vitro as follows: Reelin-expressing (Reelin \u03e9 ) preplate cells are generated, followed by the production of Ctip2 \u03e9 DL neurons, and finally, Satb2 \u03e9 and Cux1 \u03e9 UL neurons (Shen et al., 2006; [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . However, in mouse embryonic stem cell (ESC)-derived cortical cells, Cux1 \u03e9 and Satb2 \u03e9 UL neurons are underrepresented compared with observed cell proportions in vivo, and the UL neuron number is influenced by culture conditions (i.e., low-density vs aggregate culture; [CITATION_3] . Lowdensity culture conditions are also insufficient to effectively in-duce UL neurons in human ESCs and induced pluripotent stem cells [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . These observations suggest that the full complement of UL neuron production may require progenitor cells to integrate intrinsic and extrinsic cues to enable their differentiation.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "1813476",
